 	change git username and  mail globally(for all repositories):

git config --global user.name "John Doe"
      git config --global user.email "john.doe@example.com"

	verify the changes:  check global configuration
git config --global --list


 	change git username locally(for a specific repository):

cd /path/to/your/repository
git config user.name "Jane Smith"
git config user.email "jane.smith@example.com"

	verify the changes: check local configuration
 git config --list


	GIT BASIC COMMANDS:

	cloning a repository:
      git clone <repository-url>

	Check status:
      git status
 
	add changes to staging area:
      git add . / git add <file>

	commit changes: 
      git commit -m "Your commit message"

	push changes to remote repository: 
      git push origin <branch-name>

	pull changes from a remote repository: 
      git pull origin <branch-name>

	create a new branch: 
      git branch <branch-name>

	switch between branches:
      git checkout <branch-name>

	merge a branch: 
git merge <branch-name>

	create a new commit and push:
      git commit -m "Your commit message"
git push



	GIT SPECIFIED COMMANDS:

	add remote repository:
 git remote add origin <repository-url>

	view remotes: 
git remote -v


	USEFUL GIT COMMANDS FOR ADVANCED USERS:

	stash changes:
 git stash

	revert a commit: 
git revert <commit-hash>

	reset changes: 
git reset --hard

	view git log: 
git log

	tagging a commit:
 git tag <tag-name> <commit-hash>

	git worktrees: 
git worktree add <path> <branch-name>

	git restore: 
git restore <file>

	git sparse checkout:  
git sparse-checkout set <folder-name> {new in git 2.25}

	create a new repository:
 gh repo create <repo-name> --public

	create pull request:
 gh pr create --title "Add New Feature" --body "Description of feature" --base main --head feature-branch

	list all issues: 
gh issue list

	check out a pull request:
 gh pr checkout <pr-number>

	github actions: 
gh workflow run <workflow-name.yml>

	github sponsors: 
gh sponsor add <username> --amount <amount-per-month>


